<br>
I created Sinadar (high elf) on Vallon Zek because I like the description of the class: having elemental pet protectors and being the second best nukers in the game (even though as the game evolved we became the third most powerful nukers behind druids).<br>
<br>
Unfortunately, I knew nothing of what stats to pick, so I put 25 points into strength and 5 into wisdom when I created Sinadar. I joined a pretty active GvE/PvP guild called Knights of Vallon (they disbanded a few months ago), and learned alot about PvP (as well as the limitations of mages in PvP BTW).<br>
<br>
What I came to love about playing Sinadar up to level 31 was the self sufficiency of soloing with a pet, the different strategies needed to take down mobs solo, and the damage output of the class (both when soloing and in groups).<br>
<br>
When Tallon Zek went coin-only loot, I decided to make a new mage (Aedwen) on TZ with what I thought the best stat bonuses would be upon character creation. I put 20 into int and 10 into stamina (for the added HPs when leveling).<br>
<br>
Anyway, I still enjoy playing a magician. Yes I have complaints about the class, as many of you do. But I think the advantages far outweigh the shortcomings of the class. I'm now level 60, and I still enjoy soloing and fighting in groups. <br>
<br>
The classes I enjoy partnering with most are other mages (groups where 2 or 3 DSed earth pets are tanking are very powerful), enchanters (for slowing mobs, speeding pets, clarity and nuking), and necros (fear kiting is a powerful strategy). I also enjoy outdoor zones the most, for mobility.<br>
<br>
Raiding is often boring, but it's a requirement to getting loot and spells. In terms of PvP mages are at a defensive disadvantage, mainly because I still need my epic pet (only need earth staff).<br>
<br>
Anyway, those are my thoughts on the subject.<br>
<br>
Aedwen, 60 high elf mage, Tallon Zek<br>
